{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ed44a3ef-af8f-4fcb-acd3-bd588af31b3f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert <file>.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or ephemeral debug container: `kubectl debug -it <pod> --image=mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk:8.0 --target=<container>`\n- For production, prefer **`dotnet-monitor`** — it exposes an HTTP endpoint to collect traces on-demand without exec'ing in.\n- If you need OS-level context (kernel stacks, off-CPU time), use **`perf`** or **`dotnet-trace`** with `--format Speedscope` combined with `perf record`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e03ed587-8656-4ca2-9d53-1a25a7cb8354","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise, practical answer.","outputTokens":374,"requestId":"2C43:1EA0BA:137879B:16094BB:69F94719"},"id":"e01e4f3f-dce8-43f0-aaca-e5569913a7df","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:25:55.332Z","parentId":"349237d9-4c4c-4853-8c35-46ed462842c2"}
